00:01:10.890 --> 00:01:17.350
And this is my first coming
out party with "Spellbound."

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:18.630
A little bit about me--

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:24.870
I am part of a small group
of practitioners of magicians

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:29.660
that do not pretend in any way
whatsoever to have superpowers.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:32.600
I acknowledge right up
front that it's all science.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:35.390
It is all planning
and preparation

00:01:35.390 --> 00:01:39.920
and the art of misdirection and
understanding human behavior.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:41.510
And most magicians
are not that way.

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:43.842
But there are some
great examples

00:01:43.842 --> 00:01:45.550
of people that have
had this approach are

00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:48.470
like Penn and Teller, who
for decades have acknowledged

00:01:48.470 --> 00:01:50.970
that it's all trickery and some
of the great sleight of hand

00:01:50.970 --> 00:01:52.920
artists as well.

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:54.740
Which is why I wrote
this book, "The Seven

00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:57.410
Principles of Illusion"

00:01:57.410 --> 00:01:59.390
Don't call them
magic police on me.

00:01:59.390 --> 00:02:03.140
These are just principles,
fundamental principles.

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:06.770
I've tried very hard not
to ruin anyone's magic show

00:02:06.770 --> 00:02:09.060
with this book.

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:11.570
I do want to take you through
a couple of the principles.

00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:15.260
And it starts with a
story out of Hollywood.

00:02:15.260 --> 00:02:17.060
I live in Los Angeles.

00:02:17.060 --> 00:02:21.230
And my good friend, Edgar
Wright, the film director--

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:24.860
"Shaun of the Dead," "Hot Fuzz,"
"Scott Pilgrim vs. The World"--

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:26.259
can throw those
up on the screen.

00:02:26.259 --> 00:02:27.800
He asked me to come
over to his house

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:29.990
and teach him how
a magician thinks.

00:02:29.990 --> 00:02:34.460
And Edgar, as you can
imagine, is really

00:02:34.460 --> 00:02:37.720
into con games and deception.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:39.710
And he has a movie
that's coming out

00:02:39.710 --> 00:02:42.470
next month called
"Baby Driver," which

00:02:42.470 --> 00:02:44.912
is about a getaway
driver for heists.

00:02:44.912 --> 00:02:47.120
So I was not surprised when
he called me up and asked

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:51.350
me to come over and teach him
how a magician and a con man

00:02:51.350 --> 00:02:53.600
thinks.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:55.560
The afternoon did not
get off to a great start.

00:02:55.560 --> 00:02:58.256
I showed up about
15 minutes late.

00:02:58.256 --> 00:02:59.630
I was with my
friend, Blake Vogt,

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:02.389
who's a fantastic magician
and trick creator.

00:03:02.389 --> 00:03:03.680
And we couldn't find the house.

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:05.300
And we were
apologizing profusely.

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:08.270
But everything was fine
once we started performing

00:03:08.270 --> 00:03:09.990
tricks in the living room.

00:03:09.990 --> 00:03:11.180
Edgar was happy.

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:12.560
We were happy.

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:13.580
But then we finished.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:17.180
And Edgar said, show
me your best trick.

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:20.030
And we're like, Edgar, we
just-- we just showed--

00:03:20.030 --> 00:03:22.580
we just did our coolest stuff.

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.950
But OK.

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:26.152
We have an idea.

00:03:26.152 --> 00:03:27.110
Do you have a driveway?

00:03:27.110 --> 00:03:29.069
Do you have an outdoor
space that we can go to?

00:03:29.069 --> 00:03:30.735
And Edgar said, well,
I have a backyard.

00:03:30.735 --> 00:03:32.160
Let's go to the
backyard instead.

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:34.350
So we went out through the
kitchen to the veranda.

00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:37.310
And we stood in this
lovely backyard.

00:03:37.310 --> 00:03:41.420
And I said to Edgar,
name any playing card--

00:03:41.420 --> 00:03:43.520
absolute free choice.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:45.530
He said five of hearts.

00:03:45.530 --> 00:03:50.510
And then we said, point
anywhere you want in the yard.

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:53.090
And he pointed at a
bush at about 2 o'clock

00:03:53.090 --> 00:03:54.654
from where we were standing.

00:03:54.654 --> 00:03:56.570
And I said, I want you
to go over to that bush

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:59.840
and get down in the dirt at the
mulch at the base of that bush

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:00.472
and dig.

00:04:00.472 --> 00:04:01.430
And that's what he did.

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:03.620
And he found a folded
up playing card.

00:04:03.620 --> 00:04:06.830
And it was the five hearts.

00:04:06.830 --> 00:04:08.675
Edgar lost his shit.

00:04:08.675 --> 00:04:11.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:11.510 --> 00:04:15.710
Now, normally I keep the
method behind a secret

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:17.480
like this to myself.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:18.410
I do not share.

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:19.790
I do not reveal the secrets.

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:23.210
But because Edgar had asked
me to come over and teach him

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:27.980
how a magician thinks, Blake
and I pulled out an iPad

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:30.730
and we played him
this video here.

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:39.640
This is Blake burying 52 playing
cards in Edgar's backyard

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:42.550
three hours before the meeting.

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:47.530
And we memorized exactly
where they were going.

00:04:47.530 --> 00:04:52.360
Now this is how magic works.

00:04:52.360 --> 00:04:54.830
It's not smoke and mirrors.

00:04:54.830 --> 00:04:56.200
It's not dancing ladies.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:57.820
It's forethought.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:58.990
It's anticipation.

00:04:58.990 --> 00:05:00.590
It's planning.

00:05:00.590 --> 00:05:03.310
And as a puzzler
and a magician, I

00:05:03.310 --> 00:05:08.080
operate in that intersection
between preparation

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:10.720
and misdirection.

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:16.480
Now, what this involved
was a principle called

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:19.520
"the illusion of free choice."

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:20.960
And here's what
that principle is.

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:23.480
This is one of the meatier
chapters of my book,

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:25.370
the Illusion of Free Choice.

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:30.390
It basically states that if you
can get your audience believing

00:05:30.390 --> 00:05:33.840
that they are dictating
how a trick goes,

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:37.626
they will buy into
the illusion more.

00:05:37.626 --> 00:05:39.000
Blake and I did
not make this up.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.390
Think about this.

00:05:40.390 --> 00:05:43.920
When was the last time
that you had a project

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:46.470
that you were trying to
get your boss to approve

00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:48.750
and in order to
get your approval,

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:51.090
you convinced her it was
her idea to begin with.

00:05:51.090 --> 00:05:52.331
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:52.331 --> 00:05:52.830
Right?

00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:54.288
That's the illusion
of free choice.

00:05:54.288 --> 00:05:56.340
Or if you're in a sales
meeting, if you're

00:05:56.340 --> 00:05:59.460
trying to sell your
product, you would probably

00:05:59.460 --> 00:06:01.500
have more success if
you're able to convince

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:03.390
the person on the
other side of the table

00:06:03.390 --> 00:06:06.720
that it's their idea rather
than strong arming them

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:09.250
with a hard sell.

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:14.080
Now, I want to talk a little bit
about the social science of how

00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:19.150
this works, of why the illusion
of free choice and choice

00:06:19.150 --> 00:06:20.800
itself is so effective.

00:06:20.800 --> 00:06:24.700
And it involves a
experiment in the year 2000

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:28.570
by two French scientists,
Nicolas Gueguen

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:30.699
and Alexandre Pascual.

00:06:30.699 --> 00:06:32.740
Those are the names of
the two French scientists.

00:06:32.740 --> 00:06:37.780
And it involved a
theory called "you

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:40.960
are free to accept or refuse."

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:43.870
So here's the experiment
that they did.

00:06:43.870 --> 00:06:47.440
They took a young man and they
had him go into a bus station

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:49.480
and ask to one group
of people, may I

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:52.360
please have change for the bus?

00:06:52.360 --> 00:06:54.849
And he was given a
certain amount of money.

00:06:54.849 --> 00:06:56.890
And then that young man
went into the bus station

00:06:56.890 --> 00:06:59.170
and asked another
group of people,

00:06:59.170 --> 00:07:01.300
may I please have
change for the bus?

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:04.510
But you are free to
accept or refuse.

00:07:04.510 --> 00:07:08.030
Basically, reminding
people of their free will,

00:07:08.030 --> 00:07:09.780
which is so, so important to us.

00:07:09.780 --> 00:07:12.430
We, as human beings,
are wired to want to be

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:14.680
able to choose things freely.

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:19.090
And the results were the first
group, 5% of the people--

00:07:19.090 --> 00:07:19.810
I'm sorry.

00:07:19.810 --> 00:07:22.057
10% of the people gave
him money for the bus.

00:07:22.057 --> 00:07:24.640
And then the second group that
he reminded of their free will,

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:29.170
47.5% of the people gave--
a nearly 5% increase.

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:31.754
And what's more, is the
people that gave money--

00:07:31.754 --> 00:07:33.420
because they were
reminded of their free

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:35.380
will-- also gave more money.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:36.830
The denomination was higher.

00:07:36.830 --> 00:07:38.621
So when you are reminded
of your free will,

00:07:38.621 --> 00:07:42.460
you are more compliant and more
cooperative and more obliging.

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:45.190
And magicians know this.

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:48.640
Now there is something else
called the "choice-supportive

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:52.960
bias," which means that
when you choose something,

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:56.350
when you discover something,
when you have your own idea,

00:07:56.350 --> 00:08:00.040
you will defend to
that idea to the death.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:05.020
You will defend it even
in the face of data

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:06.610
that says that you're wrong.

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:09.430
You hold on to your
own ideas deeply.

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:11.717
And magicians know this as well.

00:08:11.717 --> 00:08:13.300
And we take advantage
of this as well.

00:08:13.300 --> 00:08:15.710
We have something
that we like to do,

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:19.090
which is called
a "leave behind,"

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:22.907
a "leave behind," which is--

00:08:22.907 --> 00:08:24.490
well, let me give
you an example that.

00:08:24.490 --> 00:08:28.120
It's as if I were doing the
magic coloring book, which

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:30.484
is something you probably
saw at a kids show

00:08:30.484 --> 00:08:31.400
when you were younger.

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:33.940
The magic coloring book
is you flip through it,

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:34.990
and it's blank.

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:36.448
And then you flip
through it again,

00:08:36.448 --> 00:08:37.940
and there are black
lined drawings.

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:38.700
And then you flip
through it again,

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:40.510
and those drawings
are now colored.

00:08:40.510 --> 00:08:42.220
And it's cut like
a fashion magazine.

00:08:42.220 --> 00:08:45.064
There are different ways that
you can flip through the book.

00:08:45.064 --> 00:08:47.230
I think it's OK that I'm
spoiling the magic coloring

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:48.940
book.

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:52.810
But then after the show when
you're the magician, after you

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:59.880
leave, you, by accident, leave
behind an all-blank version

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:02.220
of the magic coloring
book that you can also

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:05.760
buy for $5 at hocuspocus.com.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:07.180
It's a great investment.

00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:09.900
And when you discover
that yourself when--

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:13.610
or maybe, I can't
tell you how many--

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:18.080
I've done a trick with an
object that's not quite fair.

00:09:18.080 --> 00:09:22.040
And then I will leave a
normal object in the trash

00:09:22.040 --> 00:09:24.050
can on the way out.

00:09:24.050 --> 00:09:27.710
I can't tell you how many
people will go like, hmm.

00:09:27.710 --> 00:09:30.500
I'm going to go check that out
because I'm curious and clever.

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:35.600
And when you discover that,
when you take your own freewill

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:39.320
and you discover
that, the illusion

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:41.480
becomes absolutely bulletproof.

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:44.810
So there's a wonderful
example from history

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:46.880
of this being effective.

00:09:46.880 --> 00:09:49.910
And it's World War II.

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:52.490
It's April 30, 1943.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:56.690
And a body is found
floating in the Atlantic

00:09:56.690 --> 00:09:59.150
off the coast of Huelva, Spain--

00:09:59.150 --> 00:10:01.520
found by a Spanish fisherman.

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:06.140
The body is in military khakis
kept afloat by a life jacket.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:12.440
And chained to the dead man's
wrist was a locked briefcase.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:14.630
Now an inspection
of the man's wallet

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:19.040
revealed that his name was Major
William Martin of the British

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:20.420
Navy.

00:10:20.420 --> 00:10:23.900
Major Willie Martin, however,
was just an illusion.

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:31.820
He was conjured by a hush-part
of the British Secret Service.

00:10:31.820 --> 00:10:35.520
I forget the name
of the actual--

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:38.540
it's like M-17 or
something like that, M-17.

00:10:38.540 --> 00:10:42.690
But it was part of the
British Secret Service.

00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:48.300
And they went through a
great number of details

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:50.700
to buttress this
illusion that became

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:53.730
known as Operation Mincemeat.

00:10:53.730 --> 00:10:54.990
That's what it was called.

00:10:54.990 --> 00:10:57.330
Have you heard of that
before, Operation Mincemeat?

00:10:57.330 --> 00:10:58.697
Here's what they did.

00:10:58.697 --> 00:10:59.280
I'll show you.

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:01.920
This is a picture
of the actual body

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:03.630
that was found in the water.

00:11:03.630 --> 00:11:05.650
They took a cadaver.

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:08.820
And put it in military garb.

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:12.840
They took out an
obituary, a death notice

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:14.640
in the evening paper.

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:17.170
And they also had in his wallet
a picture of his girlfriend.

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:21.330
So all these details to
bolster this illusion.

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:25.270
What the Allies were
banking on was that Spain--

00:11:25.270 --> 00:11:27.930
which was technically
neutral but seemed

00:11:27.930 --> 00:11:33.450
to have formed a slight
alliance with the Germans--

00:11:33.450 --> 00:11:37.080
they were banking
that the Spanish would

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:40.459
give the briefcase over
to the Germans secretly

00:11:40.459 --> 00:11:42.750
and that they would open the
contents of that briefcase

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:44.730
without anybody knowing.

00:11:44.730 --> 00:11:48.650
And inside was disinformation--

00:11:48.650 --> 00:11:51.780
disinformation that said
where the Allies were going

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:54.210
to invade from North Africa.

00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:57.120
They were perched
in North Africa.

00:11:57.120 --> 00:11:59.250
They were gonna invade
across the Mediterranean.

00:11:59.250 --> 00:12:00.833
But the Germans
didn't know whether it

00:12:00.833 --> 00:12:03.570
was going to be Greece or
Sardinia or the Balkans

00:12:03.570 --> 00:12:04.710
or Sicily.

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:07.560
But the disinformation
conveyed that it

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:09.780
was Greece and
Sardinia, which is

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:12.570
where the Germans
concentrated their defenses.

00:12:12.570 --> 00:12:16.140
And that allowed the Allies
to invade Sicily instead,

00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:18.750
which was undefended.

00:12:18.750 --> 00:12:20.400
Operation Mincemeat.

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:22.050
The Allies were what
many sociologists

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:23.490
call a "choice architect."

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:26.670
They design the
choice environment

00:12:26.670 --> 00:12:29.790
in which decisions are made.

00:12:29.790 --> 00:12:32.460
Cass Sunstein and Richard
Thaler in their book,

00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:35.490
"Nudge," really define
this quite well.

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:39.360
So nudging is the
idea for a leader

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:41.010
that you know what
decisions have

00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:43.200
to be made for your employees.

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:45.300
But you allow them
to arrive freely

00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:46.740
at the best decision themselves.

00:12:46.740 --> 00:12:47.760
That's nudging.

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:49.320
Probably the best
way to describe it

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:52.770
is you take the healthy
food in the cafeteria

00:12:52.770 --> 00:12:55.470
and you put that at a eye level.

00:12:55.470 --> 00:12:58.160
I wonder if Google should take
advantage of this strategy.

00:12:58.160 --> 00:12:58.310
Do they?

00:12:58.310 --> 00:12:58.860
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:12:58.860 --> 00:12:59.943
DAVID KWONG: That's great.

00:12:59.943 --> 00:13:01.650
So they nudge you here.

00:13:01.650 --> 00:13:04.757
But everybody knows where
the pizza is, right?

00:13:04.757 --> 00:13:05.590
You had pizza today.

00:13:05.590 --> 00:13:08.344
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:11.100 --> 00:13:12.750
Let's see.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:14.280
A choice architect
will design ways

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:17.580
to help people make choices
that they themselves think

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:19.950
are better-- choice architect.

00:13:19.950 --> 00:13:22.980
Dwight D. Eisenhower has
a great quote that I love.

00:13:22.980 --> 00:13:24.720
And I'll put that up
on the screen, which

00:13:24.720 --> 00:13:27.090
is "Leadership is the
art of getting people

00:13:27.090 --> 00:13:31.900
to want what must be done,"
Dwight D. Eisenhower.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:35.320
Now, here's a here's a cool
trick that you can try at home,

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:36.850
how you can be a
choice architect

00:13:36.850 --> 00:13:38.510
and alter the
choice environment.

00:13:38.510 --> 00:13:41.030
So if you have somebody choose
a playing card-- pick a card,

00:13:41.030 --> 00:13:41.950
any card--

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:43.480
let's say it's the
queen of hearts.

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:45.056
And you figure out what it is.

00:13:45.056 --> 00:13:46.930
We can talk afterward
about a variety of ways

00:13:46.930 --> 00:13:49.221
that you can figure out what
the card is and shuffle it

00:13:49.221 --> 00:13:49.900
and control it.

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:53.380
But the reveal should
be the following.

00:13:53.380 --> 00:13:57.974
You're going to layout four
cards for your audience.

00:13:57.974 --> 00:13:59.890
You're going to put one
card in front of them.

00:13:59.890 --> 00:14:02.410
The next card will be the chosen
card, the queen of hearts,

00:14:02.410 --> 00:14:04.160
then a third card, and
then a fourth card.

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:06.760
And you're going to say
to your audience member,

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:08.962
choose any card.

00:14:08.962 --> 00:14:10.420
And most of the
time, they're going

00:14:10.420 --> 00:14:11.830
to go for the queen of hearts.

00:14:11.830 --> 00:14:12.910
Why?

00:14:12.910 --> 00:14:17.500
Because the first card is
too obvious of a choice.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:19.810
And the third card
and the fourth card

00:14:19.810 --> 00:14:22.780
you've placed just far
enough away on the table

00:14:22.780 --> 00:14:26.230
that they have to uncomfortably
get up to touch the cards.

00:14:26.230 --> 00:14:28.630
So they'll go for
the second one there.

00:14:28.630 --> 00:14:30.580
That's being a choice architect.

00:14:30.580 --> 00:14:37.460
Now, you might be wondering
is illusion inherently

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:40.620
deceptive and manipulative?

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:43.590
Well, I am trying to
do something different

00:14:43.590 --> 00:14:44.260
with this book.

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:47.880
I believe that illusion,
there is a more positive way

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:50.460
that you can command your
life, and be in control,

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:53.020
and be one, two, three steps
ahead of everybody else.

00:14:53.020 --> 00:14:54.990
So just think about
this the next time

00:14:54.990 --> 00:14:58.500
you are in a negotiation.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:02.220
Think about how you can
be a choice architect

00:15:02.220 --> 00:15:05.400
and empower the person on
the other side of the table

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:09.090
so that they can make decisions
that are good for themselves,

00:15:09.090 --> 00:15:12.240
and good for both of
you, and everybody wins.

00:15:12.240 --> 00:15:13.740
Now I want to talk
a little bit more

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:16.620
about the backyard card
trick with Edgar Wright.

00:15:16.620 --> 00:15:18.120
Because there were
some ways that we

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:21.870
were able to enhance
that illusion with what

00:15:21.870 --> 00:15:24.810
I like to call the
"illusion of spontaneity."

00:15:24.810 --> 00:15:30.720
I mentioned that we showed up
three hours before the meeting

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:31.470
to bury cards.

00:15:31.470 --> 00:15:35.070
But we were able to sell
the illusion of spontaneity

00:15:35.070 --> 00:15:39.210
by showing up for the meeting
15 minutes late on purpose

00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:40.260
and saying, sorry.

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:41.512
We couldn't find the house.

00:15:41.512 --> 00:15:42.720
We've never been here before.

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:45.249
We're sorry that we're late.

00:15:45.249 --> 00:15:47.290
And then we were in his
living room doing tricks.

00:15:47.290 --> 00:15:50.640
And we waited for him to
ask us to do one more trick.

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:53.700
We did not offer to
do a final trick.

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:54.450
We waited for him.

00:15:54.450 --> 00:15:57.570
It was his idea to see one more.

00:15:57.570 --> 00:16:01.320
And then I suggested, let's
go out to the driveway

00:16:01.320 --> 00:16:02.700
to do a trick outside.

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:05.440
And I let him upgrade us
to his lovely backyard.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:07.440
Now of course, if he had
agreed to the driveway,

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:09.932
we would have
pivoted and suggested

00:16:09.932 --> 00:16:10.890
the backyard ourselves.

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:12.450
But we didn't need to.

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:14.610
We put everything in his hands.

00:16:14.610 --> 00:16:16.900
Now, once we were
in the backyard,

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:20.010
you're probably wondering, how
did we get him to point right

00:16:20.010 --> 00:16:21.960
where the five hearts was?

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:24.820
And I'm not going to tell you.

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:25.500
No.

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:27.360
We used a lot of
suggestion and influence

00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:28.540
to get him to do that.

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:31.440
But I will say that the
important technique that we use

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:34.740
is that we were able to be in
control of the narrative, which

00:16:34.740 --> 00:16:38.140
is another big thing in magic,
which is controlling the story.

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:40.440
And just after the
trick, we started

00:16:40.440 --> 00:16:43.770
to reinforce right away, you
could have pointed anywhere

00:16:43.770 --> 00:16:44.550
you wanted.

00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:48.060
And every time I run into
him at a cocktail party

00:16:48.060 --> 00:16:50.309
or at a friend's party
and the story comes up,

00:16:50.309 --> 00:16:52.350
hey, remember that trick
we did in your backyard?

00:16:52.350 --> 00:16:54.240
You could've pointed
anywhere you wanted.

00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:56.220
You pointed right
where the card was.

00:16:56.220 --> 00:16:59.619
And I'm always, always
still working on this trick

00:16:59.619 --> 00:17:00.660
and improving this trick.

00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:06.200
Magicians can manipulate
your memory of what happened.

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:11.400
So I'm done with this.

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:13.390
We can take that down.

00:17:13.390 --> 00:17:15.359
I'm going to demonstrate
some tricks for you.

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:22.750
I didn't sneak in here yesterday
and bury 52 playing cards.

00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:23.880
But I can.

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:27.852
Let's have a little fun
with the playing cards.

00:17:27.852 --> 00:17:28.890
Where did I put that?

00:17:33.255 --> 00:17:34.730
I had an open one.

00:17:34.730 --> 00:17:35.800
Oh, no?

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:37.520
Am I crazy?

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:38.020
OK.

00:17:38.020 --> 00:17:39.020
We'll open a new pack.

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:39.520
Oh, no.

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:40.630
Here we go.

00:17:40.630 --> 00:17:41.710
OK.

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:48.610
So instead of one
card, let's try

00:17:48.610 --> 00:17:51.917
for a number of playing cards.

00:17:51.917 --> 00:17:54.000
And we'll have a number
of playing cards selected.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:54.930
Actually, you know what?

00:17:54.930 --> 00:17:55.560
Take that back.

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:56.350
Let's start with one card.

00:17:56.350 --> 00:17:57.850
Let's start with
one signed card.

00:17:57.850 --> 00:18:00.780
I'll show you how a magician
can control a single playing

00:18:00.780 --> 00:18:02.380
card in the deck.

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:04.110
So I'm going to come right here.

00:18:04.110 --> 00:18:05.360
I'm going to come to you, sir.

00:18:05.360 --> 00:18:07.230
I'm gonna have you
choose any card you like.

00:18:07.230 --> 00:18:08.130
Oh, the top card.

00:18:08.130 --> 00:18:08.760
He's that guy.

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:09.260
OK.

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:10.842
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:10.842 --> 00:18:11.800
That's quite all right.

00:18:11.800 --> 00:18:16.050
You are going to sign it so
it's the only card like that.

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:18.827
How do you know I didn't
want you to take that card?

00:18:18.827 --> 00:18:20.160
It's like-- no, not on the back.

00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:21.240
The back is too
easy for me to find.

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:22.000
Right there on the face.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:22.620
It's OK if I see it.

00:18:22.620 --> 00:18:24.270
It's fine because
you are now making

00:18:24.270 --> 00:18:27.750
it a unique card, the only
card with your signature.

00:18:27.750 --> 00:18:29.400
Thank you for your help.

00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:30.300
What is your name?

00:18:30.300 --> 00:18:31.140
AUDIENCE: Matthew.

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:31.500
DAVID KWONG: Matthew?

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:31.920
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:18:31.920 --> 00:18:32.220
DAVID KWONG: Great.

00:18:32.220 --> 00:18:33.180
Thank you so much.

00:18:33.180 --> 00:18:34.170
OK.

00:18:34.170 --> 00:18:39.100
So we have Matthew's
six of clubs.

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:42.252
This is how a magician
can track a single playing

00:18:42.252 --> 00:18:42.960
card in the deck.

00:18:42.960 --> 00:18:46.470
So these are called overhand
shuffle, as you know,

00:18:46.470 --> 00:18:49.440
overhand shuffles.

00:18:49.440 --> 00:18:53.440
This is a-- it's a
bit of a racist term.

00:18:53.440 --> 00:18:54.780
It's called the Hindu shuffle.

00:18:54.780 --> 00:18:57.810
And that's because that's how
many people shuffle in Asia.

00:18:57.810 --> 00:19:01.290
It's a 19th century term,
or maybe even earlier.

00:19:01.290 --> 00:19:03.700
My father from Hong
Kong shuffles this way.

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:06.270
So I'm allowed to
make that joke.

00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:08.310
I think we still call
it the Hindu shuffle.

00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:10.260
These are, of course, overhand--

00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:12.350
I mean riffle shuffles.

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:15.870
Everyone can shuffle
this way, right?

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:19.740
And we have what's called
a faro shuffle, F-A-R-O,

00:19:19.740 --> 00:19:22.590
which is an old French
card game, F-A-R-O.

00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:26.010
And that's when you split
the cards in half like this.

00:19:26.010 --> 00:19:28.815
And they spring together
in such a fashion.

00:19:28.815 --> 00:19:31.620
F-A-R-O.

00:19:31.620 --> 00:19:34.780
So Matthew, you
chose a playing card.

00:19:34.780 --> 00:19:36.210
You chose the six of clubs.

00:19:36.210 --> 00:19:40.782
And my goal here is to control
it to the top of the pack.

00:19:40.782 --> 00:19:42.740
With a little snap my
fingers, I should be able

00:19:42.740 --> 00:19:45.780
get one card, the six
of clubs, to come back

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:47.400
to the top of the pack, right?

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:49.710
Now, this is where it gets
a little more complicated.

00:19:49.710 --> 00:19:51.210
I'll take the six of clubs.

00:19:51.210 --> 00:19:55.540
I'll place it about
halfway down, push it in,

00:19:55.540 --> 00:19:58.690
and if I stopped my fingers,
I should be able to get one--

00:19:58.690 --> 00:20:02.650
oh-- one card to come back
to the top of the pack.

00:20:02.650 --> 00:20:03.730
All right.

00:20:03.730 --> 00:20:05.975
Let's try this again.

00:20:05.975 --> 00:20:06.975
I'll give it a few cuts.

00:20:11.550 --> 00:20:12.675
And the six of clubs--

00:20:15.225 --> 00:20:16.107
Oh yeah.

00:20:16.107 --> 00:20:18.199
That's a good one.

00:20:18.199 --> 00:20:19.990
The six of clubs-- as
I'll snap my fingers,

00:20:19.990 --> 00:20:21.610
I should be able to get
that card to come right up

00:20:21.610 --> 00:20:22.929
back to the top of the pack.

00:20:22.929 --> 00:20:24.970
I'll give you a sporting
chance to follow the six

00:20:24.970 --> 00:20:26.107
clubs this time.

00:20:26.107 --> 00:20:27.190
I'm going to take the six.

00:20:27.190 --> 00:20:28.990
And I'm going to
leave it sticking off

00:20:28.990 --> 00:20:30.070
the top of the pack.

00:20:30.070 --> 00:20:33.190
So now, if I cut it down to
the bottom without touching it.

00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:36.561
And now it has to rise up
through about 50 other cards

00:20:36.561 --> 00:20:37.310
to get to the top.

00:20:37.310 --> 00:20:40.060
Now, I promise you it has
not gone to the top yet.

00:20:40.060 --> 00:20:41.274
That's the seven of diamonds.

00:20:41.274 --> 00:20:42.940
I'm going to take the
seven of diamonds.

00:20:42.940 --> 00:20:46.150
I'm going to push in
your card like this.

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:48.850
