values for these letters.

00:42:22.090 --> 00:42:23.900
These values never change.

00:42:26.641 --> 00:42:27.680
Let's do this.

00:42:27.680 --> 00:42:32.380
Let's go 1, 1, 3,
1, 4, 1, 4, and 1.

00:42:32.380 --> 00:42:35.710
And 1, 1, 3, 3, 1, 1, 4, and 1.

00:42:35.710 --> 00:42:39.019
And 1, 1, 3, 5, 3, 1, 4, and 1.

00:42:39.019 --> 00:42:40.060
I play a lot of Scrabble.

00:42:40.060 --> 00:42:40.560
OK.

00:42:40.560 --> 00:42:41.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:41.290 --> 00:42:45.340
I'm going to add these three
eight-letter words, which I've

00:42:45.340 --> 00:42:48.280
basically now converted to
three eight-digit numbers

00:42:48.280 --> 00:42:51.280
into a new eight-digit number.

00:42:51.280 --> 00:42:54.130
So 1 plus 1 plus 1 is--

00:42:54.130 --> 00:42:56.500
let's this nice and pretty.

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:57.790
1 plus 1 plus 1 is 3.

00:42:57.790 --> 00:42:58.990
And 1 plus 1 plus 1 is 3.

00:42:58.990 --> 00:43:02.650
Now, before I began this,
there were some puzzle pieces,

00:43:02.650 --> 00:43:04.090
as I like to call them, in play.

00:43:04.090 --> 00:43:08.590
There was a kiwi,
which Monet, you

00:43:08.590 --> 00:43:10.319
managed to find
what inside of it?

00:43:10.319 --> 00:43:11.110
AUDIENCE: A dollar.

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:12.943
DAVID KWONG: A dollar,
which came from Alex.

00:43:12.943 --> 00:43:15.470
And Alex, you have your
dollar there drying off.

00:43:15.470 --> 00:43:18.910
So take a look at the
side that you signed,

00:43:18.910 --> 00:43:20.460
the George Washington side.

00:43:20.460 --> 00:43:22.460
And you'll notice in the
lower left hand corner,

00:43:22.460 --> 00:43:25.510
there's an eight-digit
serial number.

00:43:25.510 --> 00:43:26.760
Does it start with a 3, 3?

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:27.430
AUDIENCE: It sure does.

00:43:27.430 --> 00:43:28.513
DAVID KWONG: It sure does.

00:43:28.513 --> 00:43:29.805
What's to the right of the 3?

00:43:29.805 --> 00:43:30.430
AUDIENCE: Nine.

00:43:30.430 --> 00:43:31.846
DAVID KWONG: Should
be a 9, right?

00:43:31.846 --> 00:43:32.819
3 plus 3 plus 3 is 9.

00:43:32.819 --> 00:43:34.360
What do we have to
the right of that?

00:43:34.360 --> 00:43:34.690
AUDIENCE: 9.

00:43:34.690 --> 00:43:35.540
DAVID KWONG: Should
be another one, right?

00:43:35.540 --> 00:43:36.415
1 plus 3 plus 5 is 9.

00:43:36.415 --> 00:43:37.956
What do we have to
the right of that?

00:43:37.956 --> 00:43:38.540
AUDIENCE: 8.

00:43:38.540 --> 00:43:39.623
DAVID KWONG: We have an 8.

00:43:39.623 --> 00:43:40.959
4 plus 1 plus 3 is 8.

00:43:40.959 --> 00:43:42.250
And what do we have after that?

00:43:42.250 --> 00:43:42.550
AUDIENCE: 4.

00:43:42.550 --> 00:43:43.675
DAVID KWONG: Should be a 4.

00:43:43.675 --> 00:43:45.790
Because here's where it
gets interesting, folks.

00:43:45.790 --> 00:43:48.090
4 plus 4 plus 4 is 12--

00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:49.310
carry the 1, mind you.

00:43:49.310 --> 00:43:50.880
You get a 4.

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:52.310
4 plus 2.

00:43:52.310 --> 00:43:54.640
And then we should
have a 3 at the end.

00:43:54.640 --> 00:43:56.506
And 33998423.

00:43:56.506 --> 00:43:57.880
Does that match
your dollar bill?

00:43:57.880 --> 00:43:59.796
You're damn right it
matches your dollar bill.

00:43:59.796 --> 00:44:02.332
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:07.960
Any questions?

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:09.950
Now I will take questions.

00:44:12.680 --> 00:44:13.320
Five minutes?

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:13.820
OK.

00:44:13.820 --> 00:44:16.910
Five minutes for questions
more about the book

00:44:16.910 --> 00:44:21.410
and less about this would be--

00:44:21.410 --> 00:44:23.252
I'm going to give
you the microphone.

00:44:23.252 --> 00:44:25.610
AUDIENCE: So did you
have any formal training?

00:44:25.610 --> 00:44:26.870
Or did you make all this up?

00:44:26.870 --> 00:44:27.770
DAVID KWONG: Did I have
any formal training?

00:44:27.770 --> 00:44:28.269
No.

00:44:28.269 --> 00:44:31.520
I started as a
seven-year-old kid.

00:44:31.520 --> 00:44:32.810
I started with magic sets.

00:44:32.810 --> 00:44:34.532
I started reading books.

00:44:34.532 --> 00:44:35.990
I learned from
books, which I think

00:44:35.990 --> 00:44:39.080
is the best way to learn
magic because you can watch

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:41.540
everything now on YouTube.

00:44:41.540 --> 00:44:45.334
And you end up mimicking the
performer and his style when

00:44:45.334 --> 00:44:46.250
you watch it on video.

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:47.810
But when you have
books and you're

00:44:47.810 --> 00:44:48.980
trying to figure out
how to hold your hand,

00:44:48.980 --> 00:44:51.010
you end up learning
it better that way.

00:44:51.010 --> 00:44:54.950
But the truth of
my career arc is

00:44:54.950 --> 00:44:59.630
that I did not think it was a
profession until six years ago.

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:01.370
So I've been doing
it my whole life.

00:45:01.370 --> 00:45:03.694
But I had a normal desk job.

00:45:03.694 --> 00:45:04.860
It was working in Hollywood.

00:45:04.860 --> 00:45:07.550
I was at DreamWorks Animation.

00:45:07.550 --> 00:45:11.300
And then all of a sudden,
it just kind of took off.

00:45:11.300 --> 00:45:13.181
The movie, "Now You
See Me" came along.

00:45:13.181 --> 00:45:14.930
They needed somebody
who understood movies

00:45:14.930 --> 00:45:16.640
and understood magic.

00:45:16.640 --> 00:45:18.560
And I also figured
out at the same time--

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:20.060
the light bulb
turned on-- oh, I can

00:45:20.060 --> 00:45:23.540
take my two passions,
puzzles and magic,

00:45:23.540 --> 00:45:26.540
and cross-pollinate them
and make something new.

00:45:26.540 --> 00:45:32.007
And I really am a big
proponent of cross-pollination.

00:45:32.007 --> 00:45:33.590
You take something
you're an expert in

00:45:33.590 --> 00:45:35.150
and you add it to
something else.

00:45:35.150 --> 00:45:39.431
And you produce a new product.

00:45:39.431 --> 00:45:39.930
Yes.

00:45:39.930 --> 00:45:42.120
Do we need to pass
the microphone over?

00:45:42.120 --> 00:45:44.760
AUDIENCE: So who went back
and dug up all the cards

00:45:44.760 --> 00:45:47.670
that he didn't choose
from the backyard trick?

00:45:47.670 --> 00:45:50.570
DAVID KWONG: Great question.

00:45:50.570 --> 00:45:55.680
I have told you
2/3 of the trick.

00:45:55.680 --> 00:46:04.970
And at the end of chapter three,
you find out yet another twist.

00:46:04.970 --> 00:46:09.920
And the fun thing for me is
that my friend, Edgar Wright,

00:46:09.920 --> 00:46:12.320
will be finding out
for the first time

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:14.450
next week when he gets
his hands on the book.

00:46:17.780 --> 00:46:18.470
Yes, hi.

00:46:18.470 --> 00:46:21.800
AUDIENCE: So what
is the best book

00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:23.960
you would suggest
for a child trying

00:46:23.960 --> 00:46:26.780
to get into magic tricks?

00:46:26.780 --> 00:46:30.470
DAVID KWONG: I started with
"The Klutz Book of Magic."

00:46:30.470 --> 00:46:32.490
I hope they're still making it.

00:46:32.490 --> 00:46:36.380
It comes with a ring and a
little handkerchief and a--

00:46:39.500 --> 00:46:41.570
I don't want to say--

00:46:41.570 --> 00:46:43.640
it comes with a fake
body part that you

00:46:43.640 --> 00:46:45.470
can attach to yourself.

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:46.310
That's all I'll say.

00:46:46.310 --> 00:46:48.350
But that's a great
book to start with.

00:46:48.350 --> 00:46:51.364
Also Bill Tarr's,
"Now You See It,

00:46:51.364 --> 00:46:53.030
Now You Don't," is a
great starter book.

00:46:53.030 --> 00:46:57.050
And then Mark Wilson's,
"Complete Course in Magic,"

00:46:57.050 --> 00:46:58.190
has everything in it.

00:46:58.190 --> 00:47:01.490
So yeah.

00:47:01.490 --> 00:47:04.070
Usually six or seven
years old is a good time

00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:05.690
to start with that stuff.

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:08.300
You can buy some self-working
tricks in a magic shop.

00:47:08.300 --> 00:47:09.410
That's also a great
way to get started is

00:47:09.410 --> 00:47:11.330
you buy the self-working
stuff that doesn't

00:47:11.330 --> 00:47:13.730
take sleight of hand ability.

00:47:13.730 --> 00:47:17.630
And that way your child gets
comfortable lying to people.

00:47:17.630 --> 00:47:20.348
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:21.710 --> 00:47:23.509
Yeah.

00:47:23.509 --> 00:47:24.050
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:24.050 --> 00:47:25.466
So how does writing
a book compare

00:47:25.466 --> 00:47:27.290
to writing a crossword puzzle?

00:47:27.290 --> 00:47:30.000
DAVID KWONG: Oh.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:33.170
Writing a book was torture.

00:47:33.170 --> 00:47:34.520
That's how it compares.

00:47:34.520 --> 00:47:35.890
But I made it through.

00:47:35.890 --> 00:47:37.580
It was a year of
very, very hard work.

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:44.050
A crossword puzzle,
for me, is different

00:47:44.050 --> 00:47:47.540
because there's a couple
of things going on.

00:47:47.540 --> 00:47:50.830
When I come up with
a crossword theme,

00:47:50.830 --> 00:47:54.530
I'm trying to figure out
how to fool you first.

00:47:54.530 --> 00:47:56.710
That's why I think there's
an intersection of magic

00:47:56.710 --> 00:47:57.340
and puzzles.

00:47:57.340 --> 00:48:00.160
Because a good puzzle
will misdirect the solver

00:48:00.160 --> 00:48:02.500
for a little bit of
what's going on and then

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:04.910
allowing them to
finally figure it out.

00:48:04.910 --> 00:48:08.830
But what I do think puzzles and
writing a book and magic tricks

00:48:08.830 --> 00:48:11.950
all have in common
is it's storytelling.

00:48:11.950 --> 00:48:16.330
And a good puzzle takes
you through that arc where

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:19.450
you introduce the
material, and then there

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:23.980
are twists and turns, and then
there's that climactic "aha"

00:48:23.980 --> 00:48:25.270
moment.

00:48:25.270 --> 00:48:27.070
And what is the "aha"
moment in a puzzle?

00:48:27.070 --> 00:48:30.910
The "aha" moment is when you
figure out what is going on.

00:48:30.910 --> 00:48:33.820
And the great guru of
puzzles, Will Schwartz,

00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:37.030
says that in that
"aha" moment, there

00:48:37.030 --> 00:48:39.790
is a simultaneous
thing that happens.

00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:43.400
You feel smart for
having solved it.

00:48:43.400 --> 00:48:45.430
And you also respect
the constructor

00:48:45.430 --> 00:48:47.150
for having come up with it.

00:48:47.150 --> 00:48:48.880
So that is what
happens in that moment.

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:51.790
And yeah, I enjoyed
the process very

00:48:51.790 --> 00:48:56.290
much of building a magic trick,
of having a arc to the book.

00:48:59.140 --> 00:49:02.750
AUDIENCE: So who is your
favorite magician of all time?

00:49:02.750 --> 00:49:05.704
And also who is--

00:49:05.704 --> 00:49:07.870
DAVID KWONG: My least
favorite magician of all time.

00:49:07.870 --> 00:49:10.078
AUDIENCE: Least favorite
magician, favorite magician,

00:49:10.078 --> 00:49:12.620
and the coolest person
you've ever performed for,

00:49:12.620 --> 00:49:14.120
or the coolest group.

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:15.380
DAVID KWONG: OK.

00:49:15.380 --> 00:49:18.410
My favorite magicians
have been going

00:49:18.410 --> 00:49:19.790
strong for decades and decades.

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:22.850
And Penn and Teller are
my favorite magicians.

00:49:22.850 --> 00:49:29.210
I think there's a similar
sensibility in conveying

00:49:29.210 --> 00:49:31.130
that we don't have superpowers.

00:49:31.130 --> 00:49:32.870
And I just love how
irreverent they are.

00:49:32.870 --> 00:49:33.830
And they're so clever.

00:49:33.830 --> 00:49:37.370
And they find twists and turns
to put on every magic trick.

00:49:37.370 --> 00:49:41.220
The coolest person
I've done magic for--

00:49:41.220 --> 00:49:47.810
well, it was a small party
in Hollywood for Kathleen

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:49.610
Kennedy's birthday.

00:49:49.610 --> 00:49:52.330
And she's now runs Lucasfilm
and produces all the Star Wars

00:49:52.330 --> 00:49:52.830
movies.

00:49:52.830 --> 00:49:55.730
So there were maybe 15 chairs.

00:49:55.730 --> 00:49:59.240
And it was Kathy and Steven
Spielberg and J.J. Abrams.

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:04.934
And to fool other magicians
is a great, great honor.

00:50:04.934 --> 00:50:06.725
AUDIENCE: And your
least favorite magician?

00:50:06.725 --> 00:50:09.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:11.965 --> 00:50:13.590
DAVID KWONG: We'll
talk after the show.

00:50:13.590 --> 00:50:14.997
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:14.997 --> 00:50:15.580
You know what?

00:50:15.580 --> 00:50:17.290
I actually am going
to go with that

00:50:17.290 --> 00:50:22.180
and say that magic is a
difficult, difficult trade

00:50:22.180 --> 00:50:27.220
because of one
fundamental reason.

00:50:27.220 --> 00:50:30.430
There are no intellectual
property laws

00:50:30.430 --> 00:50:33.020
that can protect a magic trick.

00:50:33.020 --> 00:50:38.440
So like a joke in
comedy, or a dance move,

00:50:38.440 --> 00:50:43.150
or a director's shot in
film, these are expressions.

00:50:43.150 --> 00:50:46.990
So every magician,
like comedians,

00:50:46.990 --> 00:50:49.820
we're kind of all frenemies,
if not straight up enemies.

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:52.427
And that's because people,
especially the old guard

00:50:52.427 --> 00:50:55.010
versus the younger guard, feel
like they're being stolen from.

00:50:55.010 --> 00:50:59.390
And there are-- as I've
broken it down in this book.

00:50:59.390 --> 00:51:02.090
And another approach is
to break down magic tricks

00:51:02.090 --> 00:51:08.510
into the finite number of
illusions that have been made.

00:51:08.510 --> 00:51:11.210
We dress them up in new ways.

00:51:11.210 --> 00:51:15.170
And the magic tricks evolve
because we put new costumes

00:51:15.170 --> 00:51:16.550
and dressing on them.

00:51:16.550 --> 00:51:18.950
So a lot of the old
guard feel stolen from.

00:51:18.950 --> 00:51:21.770
A lot of your peers
feel stolen from.

00:51:21.770 --> 00:51:25.045
And that's why it's a
very tough, small field.

00:51:29.510 --> 00:51:31.490
Teller, actually,
of Penn and Teller

00:51:31.490 --> 00:51:35.870
managed to make a great
gain a couple of years

00:51:35.870 --> 00:51:38.300
ago in a lawsuit
against somebody that

00:51:38.300 --> 00:51:42.719
had copied his trick
and was marketing it,

00:51:42.719 --> 00:51:43.760
was selling it for money.

00:51:43.760 --> 00:51:48.240
And he ended up
winning that case.

00:51:48.240 --> 00:51:50.690
AUDIENCE: So I assumed,
since things break down

00:51:50.690 --> 00:51:53.630
into small pieces, when
you watch other magicians,

00:51:53.630 --> 00:51:56.130
you probably know what's
going on most of the time.

00:51:56.130 --> 00:51:57.219
Have you ever been fooled?

00:51:57.219 --> 00:51:58.760
DAVID KWONG: I have
been fooled, yes.

00:51:58.760 --> 00:51:59.761
I do speak the language.

00:51:59.761 --> 00:52:01.468
And for the most part,
I can watch a show

00:52:01.468 --> 00:52:02.910
and know exactly
what's happening.

00:52:02.910 --> 00:52:05.510
And I appreciate it
for its execution.

00:52:05.510 --> 00:52:08.217
I can be fooled by
very good misdirection.

00:52:08.217 --> 00:52:09.800
I'm a human being
like everybody else.

00:52:09.800 --> 00:52:13.870
If somebody has a very
powerful misdirection,

00:52:13.870 --> 00:52:15.579
I'll look where I'm
not supposed to look.

00:52:15.579 --> 00:52:18.078
But then I'll immediately be
like, oh, I know what happened.

00:52:18.078 --> 00:52:19.460
And I can piece
it back together.

00:52:19.460 --> 00:52:20.960
And then there are
other times where

00:52:20.960 --> 00:52:24.110
there's a brand new
technical innovation

00:52:24.110 --> 00:52:26.751
or a new move that will
completely fool me.

00:52:26.751 --> 00:52:28.250
And I'll call my
friends immediately

00:52:28.250 --> 00:52:29.810
and be like, please, please,
tell me what happened.

00:52:29.810 --> 00:52:31.370
Please tell me what happened.

00:52:31.370 --> 00:52:33.354
And they may they
make me wait 24 hours.

00:52:33.354 --> 00:52:34.520
We call it the 24-hour rule.

00:52:34.520 --> 00:52:35.561
And then they'll tell me.

00:52:35.561 --> 00:52:39.170
But we have a term for when you
get fooled by another magician.

00:52:39.170 --> 00:52:40.960
And that's called
getting burned.

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:41.660
You get burned.

00:52:41.660 --> 00:52:45.350
And that's because we
feel it right here.

00:52:45.350 --> 00:52:48.530
AUDIENCE: Does it detract
from your enjoyment

00:52:48.530 --> 00:52:51.552
of watching magic shows that
you do see right through them?

00:52:51.552 --> 00:52:53.510
DAVID KWONG: You probably
can make the argument

00:52:53.510 --> 00:52:55.871
that I don't have
the same enjoyment

00:52:55.871 --> 00:52:56.870
that everybody else has.

00:52:56.870 --> 00:52:59.020
But I watch it now
for different reason--

00:52:59.020 --> 00:53:03.297
for execution and inspiration.

00:53:03.297 --> 00:53:04.880
AUDIENCE: How do you
think the book is

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:08.090
going to affect your
relationships with your friends

00:53:08.090 --> 00:53:11.120
and coworkers now
that you're exposing

00:53:11.120 --> 00:53:14.030
how you would manipulate
them into agreeing with you?

00:53:14.030 --> 00:53:14.780
DAVID KWONG: Haha.

00:53:14.780 --> 00:53:15.279
I see.

00:53:15.279 --> 00:53:15.840
I see.

00:53:15.840 --> 00:53:17.290
I thought you were
going to ask me

00:53:17.290 --> 00:53:19.373
how the magic community
is going to react to that,

00:53:19.373 --> 00:53:21.770
which we can also discuss.

00:53:21.770 --> 00:53:23.360
No, I think I'm going to be OK.

00:53:23.360 --> 00:53:26.360
I think that these
principles, you

00:53:26.360 --> 00:53:30.050
can put them to use
in the right way.

00:53:30.050 --> 00:53:33.920
And usually, they
are in situations

00:53:33.920 --> 00:53:37.130
that you're really in control
of and that you've planned for.

00:53:37.130 --> 00:53:42.650
And this is not a handbook
on how to walk into a bar

00:53:42.650 --> 00:53:45.090
and be able to pick up anybody.

00:53:45.090 --> 00:53:47.030
So there was a book
called "The Game"

00:53:47.030 --> 00:53:48.660
that came out that
was like that.

00:53:48.660 --> 00:53:51.734
And I really wanted this to be
different, completely different

00:53:51.734 --> 00:53:52.900
spirit that I wrote this in.

00:53:55.734 --> 00:53:57.150
AUDIENCE: Do you
have ideas on how

00:53:57.150 --> 00:53:59.024
the things you talked
about at the beginning,

00:53:59.024 --> 00:54:02.580
like the illusion of choice
and how people pick a side

00:54:02.580 --> 00:54:05.970
and they stick to it, can
be applied to politics

00:54:05.970 --> 00:54:09.000
and the current
political environment

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:10.330
and what you would do about it?

00:54:10.330 --> 00:54:13.190
Like if you were superhero
using your magician powers, what

00:54:13.190 --> 00:54:15.650
are you going to do?

00:54:15.650 --> 00:54:18.530
DAVID KWONG: Well, I
think you're right.

00:54:18.530 --> 00:54:22.370
It's very hard to sway people
when they stick to their ideas.

00:54:22.370 --> 00:54:25.740
And I don't want to
get too political.

00:54:25.740 --> 00:54:28.730
But I think we can
probably all agree

00:54:28.730 --> 00:54:33.440
that there is a master of
misdirection in the White House

00:54:33.440 --> 00:54:33.940
right now.

00:54:37.730 --> 00:54:42.140
Tommy Wonder, the
great Dutch magician,

00:54:42.140 --> 00:54:47.030
said that misdirection is
giving people something

00:54:47.030 --> 00:54:49.190
of greater interest to look at.

00:54:49.190 --> 00:54:52.380
So like bad misdirection
would be you're doing a show

00:54:52.380 --> 00:54:55.750
and then somebody drops a tray
full of metal pots and pans,

00:54:55.750 --> 00:54:57.200
and everyone's like [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:57.200 --> 00:55:00.530
But good misdirection is
something of greater interest

00:55:00.530 --> 00:55:02.960
that they can pay attention to.

00:55:02.960 --> 00:55:04.939
If I were to make a
bird appear, you're

00:55:04.939 --> 00:55:07.230
all going to-- that's like
the end of the trick, right?

00:55:07.230 --> 00:55:08.813
I've showed you an
empty handkerchief.

00:55:08.813 --> 00:55:10.040
I make a bird appear.

00:55:10.040 --> 00:55:12.510
You're not going to want to
ignore that because it's cool.

00:55:12.510 --> 00:55:13.760
And it's the end of the trick.

00:55:13.760 --> 00:55:16.370
But in that moment, I'm already
reaching for my next thing

00:55:16.370 --> 00:55:17.840
and setting up my next trick.

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:22.100
And I think that he
who shall not be named

00:55:22.100 --> 00:55:27.410
is a master at giving
us something else that

00:55:27.410 --> 00:55:31.280
takes our attention that
we're interested in.

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:33.380
[APPLAUSE]

00:55:34.380 --> 00:55:34.880
Thank you.

00:55:34.880 --> 00:55:37.930
